{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DrQ6oKmWdHotMMhWTE67re","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. The Elasticsearch backend:\n- Uses HTTPS on port 9200 (confirmed by the curl output)\n- The TLS cert has SANs for `localhost`, `*.elasticsearch.svc`, `*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`\n- The cert doesn't include `es.example.com`\n\n**Strategy:**\n1. Generate a self-signed certificate for `es.example.com` \n2. Create a TLS secret in the `elasticsearch` namespace (where the Ingress will be) OR in a namespace accessible to nginx\n3. Create an Ingress with:\n   - `ingressClassName: nginx`\n   - TLS section pointing to the new cert\n   - Backend protocol annotation set to HTTPS so nginx knows to use TLS when connecting to the service\n   - HTTP to HTTPS redirect enabled\n   - Route `es.example.com` to `es-http:9200`\n\nI'll create the Ingress in the `elasticsearch` namespace since that's where the service lives.\n\nNow I need to generate a self-signed certificate for `es.example.com` using OpenSSL with the proper subject alternative name, then create a Kubernetes secret from it and set up the Ingress resource. I should also verify that the `es-http` service selector matches the elasticsearch pods—it uses `app: elasticsearch` which should be correct. For the HTTP blocking requirement, the nginx ingress redirect handles that by default, though technically it's a 301 redirect rather than outright blocking. So HTTP requests get redirected to HTTPS, which effectively blocks direct HTTP access. Now I need to set up the Ingress resource in the elasticsearch namespace, referencing a TLS secret for es.example.com, and configure it to route to the Elasticsearch service on port 9200 with HTTPS backend protocol enabled.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2272,"cache_read_input_tokens":43422,"cache_creation":